Choose the columns of the matrix as follows: $\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}.$

First, substitute the given equation with $x$, $y$, and $z$.
$$
\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} 
x = 
\begin{pmatrix} 0  & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
x + y + z
$$
Using the given equation and the matrix definitions, we can solve for $x:$
$$
\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{vmatrix} 
x
= \begin{vmatrix} 
{begin{matrix} 0  & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{matrix}} x + y + z
\end{vmatrix}
$$
Simplifying the RHS of the equation, we get:
$$
x = \begin{vmatrix} 
{begin{matrix} 0  & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{matrix}} 
(y + z)
\end{vmatrix}
$$
Putting this back into the matrix definition, we get:
$$
\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} 
y = 
\begin{pmatrix} 0  & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
y + z
$$
Simplifying the LHS of the equation, we get:
$$
y = \begin{vmatrix} 
{begin{matrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{matrix}} 
(y + z)
\end{vmatrix}
$$
Similarly, we can solve for $z:$
$$
\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} 
z = 
\begin{pmatrix} 0  & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
y + z
$$
Simplifying the LHS of the equation, we get:
$$
z = \begin{vmatrix} 
{begin{matrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{matrix}} 
(y + z)
\end{vmatrix}
$$
Therefore, the matrix $\mathbf{M}$ is:
$$
\mathbf{M} = 
\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}.$$

