The particle is moving on the unit circle of a right-angled trigonometric triangle.
The distance that the particle travels is the hypotenuse of the triangle, which is given as:
$$\text{Hypotenuse} = \sqrt{2^2+2^2} = \sqrt{\boxed{4}} = 2$$
The time taken by the particle to complete one circle can be calculated as:
\begin{align*}\sin\left(\frac{p}{4}\right)=\frac{v}{r}\end{align*}
and
\begin{align*}\cos\left(\frac{p}{4}\right)=\frac{r}{v}\end{align*}
where $p$ is the angular momentum, $v$ is the speed of the particle, $r$ is the radius of the circle.
Using the initial position given, we can set up the equations as:
\begin{align*}\frac{3\sin\frac{t}{4}}{2}=\frac{v}{1} \rightarrow v = 3\sin\frac{t}{2}\end{align*}
and
\begin{align*}\frac{3\cos\frac{t}{4}}{2}=\frac{r}{1} \rightarrow r = 1\end{align*}
where the radius of the circle is set to 1. Substituting the values in the first equation, we get:
\begin{align*}v = \sin\left(\frac{t}{2}\right)f\end{align*}
where $f$ is a constant speed that the particle travels at.
Finally, using $v = d\frac{\text{radius}}{\text{time}}$ to find the speed of the particle:
\begin{align*}f = \frac{1}{2\pi}\left(\sqrt{4} - 2\right) \sqrt{\frac{3}{\pi}} \approx 0.1346.\end{align*}
Therefore, the speed of the particle is $f \approx 0.1346$ unit of distance per unit of time.

