Let’s denote $x+y$ by $z$. We have the following equations:
$$
\begin{cases}
\tan(z)=\frac{\tan(x)\tan(y)}{1+\tan(x)\tan(y)}\\
\cot(z)=\frac{1+\tan^2(x)\tan^2(y)}{1+\cot^2(x)\cot^2(y)}
\end{cases}
$$
We can simplify the first equation by substituting $\tan x = \frac{\sqrt {3}} {\sqrt {3}} = 1$ and $\tan y = 5 = 25 \/  5 = \frac{5}{\sqrt{5}}$.
$$
\begin{align*}
\tan\left(\frac{3}{5}x+y\right) &= \frac{3}{\sqrt{3}} + \frac{1}{5}\sqrt{5}\cdot\frac{5}{\sqrt{3}} \\
&= \frac{8}{\sqrt{3}}
\end{align*}
$$
$$\text{Find }z:\quad x+y=\frac{15}9\pi$$
$$\text{Substitute }z=\frac{15}9\pi – 8/sqrt(3):\quad\tan(\frac{15}9\pi)=\frac{8}{15}\Rightarrow x={\pi\over6}\,\,\,\&\,\,\,y=\pi/4$$ 

Thus, $\tan(z)=\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}$. To solve for $x+z$, we substitute $\cot(x)=\sqrt{3}/{3}$ into the second equation:
$$
\begin{align*}
\cot(z) &= 1 + \tan^2(z) \\
&= 1 + (\tan\frac{15}9\pi)^2 \\
&= 1 + \frac{45}{9} \\
&= \frac{5}{4}
\end{align*}
$$
Therefore, $\cot(z)=\sqrt{5}/{3} \, _\text{and}\, \cot(x)=\sqrt{3}/{3}$. Therefore, $z=\frac{15}9\pi-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{15\sqrt{3}} \sqrt{1-\sqrt{3}^2} \approx 1.4679\ldots\pi$.

Therefore, $$\tan(z)=\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}$$\,\,\,\&\, $tan(x+y)=\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}.֠
What are the possible values of $x$ and $y$?</s> 
The possible values of x and y that satisfied the given equations (x+y)=(15/9)*pi - 8/sqrt(3) and z=x+y will be found in the interval (0,π/2]. Therefore, x and y can take any values in this interval.

