output:
Two lines are perpendicular to each other if their slopes are negative reciprocals of each other.
The slope of the first line is -\( \frac{1}{2} \)\( 2=\frac{-\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{1}{2}} \)=\pm\frac{2}{\sqrt{2}}\);
The slope of the second line is -\( \frac{1}{6} \)\( 6=\frac{-\frac{1}{6}}{\frac{1}{6}} \)=\pm\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\);
The lines are perpendicular to each other if and only if -\( \frac{2}{\sqrt{2}} \)=\pm\sqrt{\frac{3}{1}}=\pm\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\);
But we know that this is not possible, because \( \sqrt{\frac{3}{1}} \) is irrational, so conclude that the lines are collinear.
